#### 2.2.4. Lagrangian vs Eulerian dynamics

In finite dimension, the tangent space to a manifold M at a point x\in M can be thought of as being the set of speeds \dot{\theta}(0) of smooth curves \theta such that \theta(0)=x. In \mathcal{P}\_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{d}), restricting our attention to geodesics and having in mind the Benamou-Brenier dynamic reformulation of optimal transport [4], we know that, formally geodesics (m\_{t})\_{t\in[-1,1]} are given as solution of continuity equations

